The author of the article expresses concern over reports of Kellogg's plans to permanently replace striking workers from the Bakery, Confectionery, Tobacco Workers and Grain Millers International during their collective bargaining negotiations. The author believes that permanently replacing striking workers is a threat to the union and its members' jobs and livelihoods. They oppose this practice and support legislation that would ban it. The author emphasizes the importance of collective bargaining in providing workers a voice and the opportunity to improve their lives while contributing to their employer's success. They assert that unions played a crucial role in building the middle class and state their unwavering support for both unions and collective bargaining. The author urges employers and unions to work out their differences at the bargaining table in a fair manner that advances both parties' interests.